Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset has 13 variables and 1599 observations. Variables are the chemical property of the wine. Most of the variables are normally distributed. There was one variable with bi-modal distribution - Volatile Acidity. Free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide data is skewed. And most of the variables do have outliers too.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

How the Alcohol effects the quality would be interesting to know. Which chemical is strongly correlated with the quality? and as we saw that one-fourth of the wine do not have citric acid, I will have to see their quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

pH level in the best quality of alcohol will be worth observing. Outliers in most of the variables would be worth investigating.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes, I created a quality_category where it categories the quality score. I divided the score into two categories - Low for score between 3-5 and high for score between 5-8.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Some plot didn’t look like a normal distribution with default binwidth, so I adjusted the binwidth which gave a better shape to the plot (normal distribution). Adjusting the binwidth also helped me in getting a bi-modal distribution which looked like a normal distribution with default binwidth.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

Citric acid and quality of the wine are not strongly correlated. At first, I thought it might be a big factor. Quality is correlated with the alcohol, pH has a correlation with the citric acid and fixed acidity. The quality is correlated with the percentage of alcohol. It would be interesting to see what percentage of alcohol makes a wine of good quality.

Residual sugar doesn’t have a strong correlation with any variable. So I removed it from the plot matrix.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship was between fixed acidity and pH with -0.683.

Multivariate Plots Section

This plot strengthens out previous assumption - if the alcohol percentage it more then, the quality might be better.

It justifies our earlier finding in the plot matrix, where there was a strong correlation between the density and the alcohol and although there is a strong correlation between alcohol and the quality it doesn’t necessarily mean the density and quality have a strong correlation.

The quality category seems to be all over the place. There doesn’t seem to be any strong correlation between the quality and the other two variables. However the fixed acidity and citric acid are strongly correlated.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

The two clear variables that do contributes to the quality of wine are the percentage of alcohol and volatile acidity. Other variables don’t strongly explain the variability in the quality of the wine.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Volatile acidity had a strong correlation with citric acid, and as volatile acidity explains the variability of the quality, I thought citric acid will also have an impact on the quality but that wasn’t to be.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

Yes, I did create models, it helped me justify the variability of quality of the wine due to various variables.

Strengths:

Very simple to use and comprehend the result.

Limitations:

Linear regression is very sensitive to the anomalies in the data.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

We can clearly see that wine with volatile acidity between 0.22 and 0.92 have a good quality score.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot (quality vs alcohol) gives an insight about the quality of the wine - Greater the percentage of alcohol greater the quality.

Plot Three

Description Three

Alcohol and Volatile acidity are the two variables which explain the 31.7% of the variability in the quality score. In our previous findings, we saw how the volatile acidity had a negative correlation which can be seen in this plot, lesser the volatile acidity better the quality. Similarly, with the alcohol, the only difference is that it is positively correlated with the quality.

Note: We can only infer the above statement. Having a low volatile acidity and a high percentage of alcohol doesn’t necessarily means the quality will be good. There are other factors that can have an effect on the quality of the wine.

Reflection

I started exploring by taking a look at the data and there types most of them were numbers except one which was an integer. Then I had a look at the descriptive statistics which gave an idea of the spread, mean, median and the quartile range. Understanding the variables help me in exploring the variables with the plot. Initially, I went with the uni-variable plots along the course I put up some questions which helped me in exploring in the later stage. Most of the variables were having a normal distribution and a few were skewed. I did encounter outlier which was surprising as well. I did create a categorical variable which grouped the quality into two groups, the quality of wine from 3 to 5 were in one group as low and 5 to 8 were in a different group as high. This variable helped me in getting deeper insights into the later stage of the exploration.

With the plot matrix, I got a clear idea of how the variables are related to one another. This matrix showed how alcohol was strongly correlated to the quality of the wine, it also helped me in selecting the variables of my interest which saved a lot of time as exploring every variable could have been tedious. I plotted some scatter plot between two variables to visualize how the variables are correlated.

In the multivariate analysis, it visualized with the categorical variable which I created in the earlier part of my exploration. The categorical variable helped in getting an insight of the quality of wine while exploring different variables at once. Finally, I created a linear model to predict the quality of the wine across different variables. Alcohol and Volatile acidity account for 31.7% of the variation in the quality. One of the most surprising things was when I found out that citric acid didn’t improve the quality of the wine.

As all the variables were either numbers or integers I initially struggle to create a categorical variable so that I could explore further - I was finding it hard to think of a categorical variable. Eventually, I did it using the quality variable.

Further, I could have explored the outlier as there were outliers in most of the variables.

Limitations in our exploration: As with our liner model I could only justify the 31.7% of variation in the quality by two variables if I would have had some more details about of the wine I could have done more in finding out the variability of the quality, The data was described in 2009 and as things changes over the time today this correlation of alcohol and volatile acidity might not be the same in today’s world.
